======================================================================
PART 1: FACTORIZATION OF FORBIDDEN VALUES
======================================================================

  Forbidden at n=6: [7, 21, 35, 39]

  7:
    Factors: 7
    Is Phi_3(k)? True at k=2
    Phi_3 product: Phi_3(2)=7

  21:
    Factors: 3 * 7
    Is Phi_3(k)? True at k=4
    Phi_3 product: Phi_3(4)=21

  35:
    Factors: 5 * 7
    Is Phi_3(k)? False
    Phi_3 product: Phi_3(2)=7 * 5

  39:
    Factors: 3 * 13
    Is Phi_3(k)? False
    Phi_3 product: Phi_3(3)=13 * Phi_3(1)=3

  35 = 5 * 7 = 5 * Phi_3(2)
  39 = 3 * 13 = Phi_3(1) * Phi_3(3)
  Note: 39 = Phi_3(1) * Phi_3(3) — product of TWO Phi_3 values!
  But 35 has factor 5 which is NOT a Phi_3 value.
  5 = Phi_5(2) = 2^4+2^3+2^2+2+1 ... no. Phi_5(2) = 31.
  5 = Phi_4(2) = 2^2+1 = 5. YES! 5 = Phi_4(2)!
  So 35 = Phi_4(2) * Phi_3(2) = 5 * 7!

  Cyclotomic polynomials at x=2:
    d   Phi_d(2)                  = 2^d-1 / ...
    1          1
    2          3
    3          7
    4          5
    5         31
    6          3
    7        127
    8         17
    9         73
   10         11
   11       2047
   12         13
   13       8191
   14         43
   15        151

  Forbidden values as products of Phi_d(2):
     7 = Phi_3(2)=7
    21 = Phi_6(2)=3 * Phi_3(2)=7
    35 = Phi_4(2)=5 * Phi_3(2)=7
    39 = Phi_12(2)=13 * Phi_6(2)=3

